They will stop only when all the avengers are part of either side. Every Avenger has a power associated with him There are some spurious avengers who will decrease the overall power of the team. Problem Description Two friends are shopping for friendship bands at a mell but face a tricky problem! The bands come in pairs inside cases where the bards are tangled together-perhaps interlocked Curting a band is not an option, so they need to figure out if there is a way to separate the bands without damaging them. The Setup Band Cases. Each case contains a pair of friendship bands, presented as a 3D cube matrix (size S x SxS Tangled Bands: Each band is represented by a sequence of movements: "u", "d", "T", "b", "T", and "t" representing up, down, front, back, left, and right respectively. Starting from a designated position in the cube matrix, each movement instruction places a unit cube (representing part of the band) sequentially, Refer the exarriple below for better understanding Important Rules: No Overlapping Bands: A particular cell within the cube matrix will not contain more than one unit cube at a time Visual Aid: The top-front-left comer of the cube matrix is (0,0,0), and the bottom-back-right corner is (S-1, 5-1, 5-1). Coordinates: If the current cell is (lyy,x) downy+T front-ly+1 back-ty-1 right=x+1 left-x-1 Example Let us say the case size is 4 x 4 x 4. For now, assume it has only one band (for purpose of understanding the placement of band in the case). The starting position of the band is (1, 0, 1), and the band sequence is 'ddderbuuullf. Applying the sequence as per co-ordinate system mentioned above, this represents a series of movements that construct the band within the cube matrix. We will visualize them as below. The 4 x 4 x 4 cube divided into 4-4x4 matrix [Layers), indexed as (Layer, Row and Column) 0000 0100 0111 0000 0000 0100 0001 0000 0000 0100 0001 0000 0000 0111 0001 0000 The last instruction connects the last unit cube of the band to the first unit cube to complate the band. The cells of the same band will not be placed above its ceils again except it's the nest cell Your Tasic Given two friendship band placements represented by their starting positions and sequences of movement instructions, determine if it is possible to separate thern without cutting any bands. Constraints 5-S40 Input First line consists of an integer representing S, the side of the cube matrix. Next Line consist of three space separated integers denoting the starting position of Band 1 Next Line consist of sequence of Band 1 placement comprising of characters from ('u'd" ", "b"," and "Y) Next Line consist of three space separated integers denoting the starting position of Band 2 Last Line consist of sequence of Band 2 placement. Output Single integer representing the maximum number of cells one band is above another when not interlocked Else print "Impossible

import java.util.*; public class SharkEscape { private static final int[] DIRECTIONS_X = {0, 1, 0, -1}; // Directions for horizontal movement private static final int[] DIRECTIONS_Y = {1, 0, -1, 0}; // Directions for vertical movement // Method to calculate the optimal path and remaining strength public static String findEscapeRoute(int rows, int cols, int[][] sharkStrength, int[][] pathTime, int initialStrength) { int startX = -1, startY = -1, destinationX = -1, destinationY = -1; // Locate the start and destination positions in the shark grid for (int i = 0; i < rows; i++) { for (int j = 0; j < cols; j++) { if (sharkStrength[i][j] == -1) { // 'S' signifies the start position startX = i; startY = j; sharkStrength[i][j] = 0; // Set the shark strength at start to 0 } else if (sharkStrength[i][j] == -2) { // 'D' signifies the destination destinationX = i; destinationY = j; sharkStrength[i][j] = 0; // Set the shark strength at destination to 0 } } } if (startX == -1 || destinationX == -1) { return "Not Possible"; } // Priority Queue for Dijkstra's algorithm: time is prioritized PriorityQueue<int[]> pq = new PriorityQueue<>((a, b) -> Integer.compare(a[0], b[0])); pq.offer(new int[]{0, startX, startY, initialStrength}); // {time, x, y, strength} // Array to store the maximum strength remaining at each cell int[][] visited = new int[rows][cols]; for (int[] row : visited) { Arrays.fill(row, -1); // Initialize with -1, meaning unvisited } // Implementing the Dijkstra’s algorithm while (!pq.isEmpty()) { int[] current = pq.poll(); int currentTime = current[0], x = current[1], y = current[2], currentStrength = current[3]; if (x == destinationX && y == destinationY) { return currentTime + " " + currentStrength; // Return the result if destination is reached } if (visited[x][y] >= currentStrength) { continue; // Skip if this position is already visited with more strength } visited[x][y] = currentStrength; // Explore all possible directions for (int direction = 0; direction < 4; direction++) { int newX = x + DIRECTIONS_X[direction]; int newY = y + DIRECTIONS_Y[direction]; if (newX >= 0 && newY >= 0 && newX < rows && newY < cols) { int sharkAtNewCell = sharkStrength[newX][newY]; int timeToMove = pathTime[newX][newY]; // Check if the strength is enough to fight the shark at the new position if (currentStrength > sharkAtNewCell) { int newStrength = currentStrength - sharkAtNewCell - 1; // Reduce strength for the shark fight and move if (newStrength >= 0) { pq.offer(new int[]{currentTime + timeToMove, newX, newY, newStrength}); } } } } } return "Not Possible"; // Return if no path is found } // Main method to read input and print the result public static void main(String[] args) { Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in); // Read grid dimensions int rows = scanner.nextInt(); int cols = scanner.nextInt(); int[][] sharkStrength = new int[rows][cols]; int[][] pathTime = new int[rows][cols]; // Read shark strength grid and identify the start (S) and destination (D) for (int i = 0; i < rows; i++) { for (int j = 0; j < cols; j++) { String cell = scanner.next(); if (cell.equals("S")) { sharkStrength[i][j] = -1; // Start position } else if (cell.equals("D")) { sharkStrength[i][j] = -2; // Destination position } else { sharkStrength[i][j] = Integer.parseInt(cell); // Shark strength in other cells } } } // Read time grid which represents time taken for each move for (int i = 0; i < rows; i++) { for (int j = 0; j < cols; j++) { pathTime[i][j] = scanner.nextInt(); // Time to move through each cell } } // Read the initial strength int initialStrength = scanner.nextInt(); scanner.close(); // Output the result from the escapeIsland method System.out.println(findEscapeRoute(rows, cols, sharkStrength, pathTime, initialStrength)); } }

Agilan, a final-semester undergraduate student, needs to reach his teammate Rabin's house to finalize their major project due in February. Rabin provides Agilan with detailed driving directions consisting of turns and distances at traffic signals. However, due to heavy traffic, Agilan makes one wrong turn while covering the correct distance. He successfully follows the remaining instructions accurately. You are given the coordinates of Rabin's house and a set of directions provided by Rabin (which include "left," "right," "straight," and "back" turns). Your task is to: Identify the specific turn Agilan made incorrectly. Determine the correct turn he should have taken. Note: Agilan starts his journey facing 'north' initially. Instructions are elaborated below for brevity: 1. left - This instructs Agilan to turn towards his left (for e.g., North to East, East to South, South to West, West to North) from wherever he is going on. 2. right - This instructs Agilan to turn towards his right from wherever he is going on. 3. straight - This instructs Agilan to go straight continuing with the same direction wherever he is going on. 4. back - This instructs Agilan to turn back (U-turn, for e.g. North to South, South to North, East to West, West to East) from wherever he is going on. Constraints 3 <= N <= 104 Distance travelled in one instruction <= 50 Input First line contains and integer 'N' - indicating number of instructions Rabin has provided to Agilan for visiting his place. Next N lines consist of N instructions each defining the direction and its corresponding distance. Last 2 lines consists of the co-ordinates (x, y space-separated integers) defining location of Agilan's residence and Rabin's residence, respectively. Output Output "No" if Agilan cannot reach Rabin's house by correcting only one turn. Output "Yes" followed by: The specific incorrect turn Agilan made. The distance covered while taking the incorrect turn. The correct turn he should have taken instead. The distance associated with the correct turn. For exact printing format refer the Examples section Time Limit (secs) 1 Examples Example 1 Input 5 right 5 left 3 left 3 right 1 right 2 0 0 0 2 Output Yes right 1 left 1 Explanation Agilan starts his journey from the coordinates (0, 0), facing north. The path he followed is represented in blue, while the correct path is depicted in orange. Upon analysis, it is evident that Agilan would have reached Rabin's residence correctly if he had followed the second-to-last instruction properly. Instead of proceeding right for 1 unit at (2, 3), he should have taken a left turn for 1 unit. Therefore, the incorrect instruction is "right 1", and the correct instruction is "left 1". com.tcs.cv.automata.ei.middleware.DocxToHtmlConverter@94f6bfb:image1.png Example 2 Input 8 straight 5 right 2 right 7 right 5 straight 1 left 2 left 3 right 4 0 0 12 14 Output No Explanation Agilan starts his journey from the coordinates (0, 0) facing north. The path he followed is represented in blue. It can be clearly deduced that by correcting exactly one path, Agilan will not be able to reach Rabin's residence (12, 14). Therefore, the answer is 'No'.
